0.body: SkyFlex is a brand new ActionScript 3 engine for the internet. SkyFlex allows you to program user interface skins, layout and logic in the ActionScript 3 and MXML languages, and additionally skinning the user interface through a subset of the CSS3 language.
0.title: SkyFlex

1.body: A Single Page Application is a website that prevents refreshing the current page when redirecting to another page; in other words, a webpage is responsible for its own physical page and for any other physical page. Single Page Applications render pages in the client side and the server side.
1.title: Single Page Applications

10.body:
The SkyFlex manifest for a website looks like the following: [package]
name = "example"
version = "0.1.0" [[source]]
path = "src"
include = true [website]
enable = true [dependencies]
10.title: Website

11.body:
The SkyFlex manifest for a library looks like the following: [package]
name = "example.util"
version = "0.1.0"
author = "Me <me@example.com>"
license = "MIT or Apache-2.0"
description = "My utilities" [[source]]
path = "src"
include = true [dependencies]
11.title: Library

12.body:
The SkyFlex manifest for a command line interface looks like the following: [package]
name = "example"
version = "0.1.0" [[source]]
path = "src"
include = true [cli]
enable = true
main-class = "example.Example" [dependencies]

14.body: A SkyFlex application renders a specific page to the user at a time.
14.breadcrumbs: Building a page » Building a page
14.title: Building a page

15.body:
Pages are MXML files containing a <s:Page> tag that explicitly sets the path rule. Here is an example: <!-- src/com/example/pages/Home.mxml -->
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<s:Page xmlns:s="http://skyflex.com/1.0" path="/"> <s:Label text="Hello world!"/>
</s:Page>
15.breadcrumbs: Building a page » Getting started » Getting started
15.title: Getting started

16.body:
MXML files insert ActionScript code through a <s:Script> tag containing code inside a <![CDATA[ ... ]]> markup. <?xml version="1.0"?>
<s:Page xmlns:s="http://skyflex.com/1.0" path="/"> <s:Script><![CDATA[ // ActionScript ]]></s:Script>
</s:Page> For initialiser code, handle the creationComplete event in the s:Page tag: <?xml version="1.0"?>
<s:Page xmlns:s="http://skyflex.com/1.0" path="/" creationComplete="initialise()"> <s:Script><![CDATA[ private function initialise():void { trace("Hello world"); } ]]></s:Script>
</s:Page>
16.breadcrumbs: Building a page » Adding a script » Adding a script
16.title: Adding a script

17.body: MXML is an eXtensible Markup Language used for expressing user interface components over the ActionScript language.
17.title: MXML reference

18.body:
A MXML file shall have a filename that identifies the name of the ActionScript class that it defines, while the parent directories after a source path determine the ActionScript package it belongs to. Given that the SkyFlex manifest defines source[0].path as "src", the following is an example MXML file defining the class com.company.max.WeatherScreen: <!-- src/com/company/max/WeatherScreen.mxml -->
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<s:HGroup xmlns:s="http://skyflex.com/1.0"> <s:Label variant="heading" value="Weather"/>
</s:HGroup>
18.title: MXML file

19.body: The convention is to assign the i prefix as the URI http://skyflex.com/1.0, identifying the SkyFlex elements and component set.
19.title: i prefix

28.body: Cascading Style Sheet (CSS) is a subset of the world wide web Cascading Style Sheet 3 language used for skinning the user interface in an expressive way over existing ActionScript definitions.
28.title: CSS reference

29.body:
The following sheet customizes the font family and weight of Label objects that are heading titles: @namespace s "http://skyflex.com/1.0"; s|Label[variant=heading] { fontFamily: segoe ui, sans; fontWeight: lighter;
}
29.title: Basic sheets

33.body: ActionScript 3 is the primary general purpose, object-oriented scripting language supported by the SkyFlex, which is based in the ECMAScript fourth edition. SkyFlex supports certain features not contained in the specification.
33.title: ActionScript reference

34.body: ActionScript 3 Language Specification ECMA-262 Third Edition ECMA-357 Second Edition
34.title: Specification

35.title: Basic programs

36.body: ActionScript defines three minimum types: void, null, and Object, of which only void and Object and its infinite subclasses are expressed by the user.
36.title: Types

37.body: The void type consists of the undefined value.
37.title: Void type

38.body: The null type consists of the null value, although no type annotation is allowed to use the null type.
38.title: Null type

39.body: The Object type represents objects containing properties in different forms.
39.title: Object type

4.body: MXMLC is an ActionScript compiler that compiles the following languages: ActionScript 3 MXML A CSS3 subset It produces the following artifacts: JavaScript modules representing physical pages; some for the client, some for the server side A JavaScript module that contains application code JavaScript source maps mapping back JavaScript to the original ActionScript and MXML sources Static media including images and sound The resulting artifacts may be mounted into a live website through the SkyFlex command line.
4.title: MXMLC

40.body: Object may be the null value, except its subclasses Number, float, int, uint and Boolean. Object may be the undefined value, except all of its subclasses.
40.title: Nullability

41.body: The types Number, int, uint, float, Boolean and String are final subclasses of Object that are considered primitive types. Type Description Number IEEE 754 double precision floating point. Includes NaN, +Infinity and -Infinity. float IEEE 754 single precision floating point. Includes NaN, +Infinity and -Infinity. int Signed 32 bit integer uint Unsigned 32 bit integer Boolean Boolean that is false or true String String consisting of UTF-16 code units
41.title: Primitive types

42.title: Array type

46.body: The Namespace type is used both for representing ActionScript 3 namespaces and XML namespaces.
46.title: Namespace type

47.body: The nullable type T? or ?T is a compile time type enforcing that a type contains null. Note that almost all types contain null already.
47.title: Nullable type

48.body: The non nullable type T! is a compile time ensuring that a type does not contain null.

48.title: Non nullable type

8.body: The project manifest is a TOML file with the name skyflex.toml, placed in the top directory of a project, that describes an optional SkyFlex workspace and a SkyFlex package. Any SkyFlex project shall contain the SkyFlex manifest in order to, for example, compile.
